<h1 class="hero-h">How to train <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">your team on Claude.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Buying Claude seats does not change how your team works. Training does — if it's the right training. Most internal AI training fails the same way: a 60-minute generic demo, polite nodding, then no behavior change. This is the playbook for training that actually sticks.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The principle</span><h2 class="h2">Train on workflows, not features</h2><p class="body">Generic AI training ("here's what an LLM is, here's how prompting works") produces awareness, not adoption. Workflow-specific training ("here is exactly how you, the sales rep, will draft a follow-up email using this Project") produces adoption.</p><p class="body">Rule: every training session should leave the participant with one specific workflow they can do that afternoon, faster than they did yesterday.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Week 1</span><h2 class="h2">Foundations (90 minutes total)</h2><h3 class="h3">Session 1: What Claude is and how we use it (30 min)</h3><ul class="ul"><li>What Claude is, in one slide.</li><li>What we use it for here (specific workflows we've already built).</li><li>What we do NOT use it for (data classifications, policy summary).</li><li>How to access (login, Projects you have access to).</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Session 2: Prompting basics (30 min)</h3><ul class="ul"><li>How to write a clear prompt (with 3 examples in the team's actual workflow context).</li><li>How to refine when the output is off ("more concise," "add an objection-handling section," "shorter").</li><li>How to use Claude Projects vs the standalone chat.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Session 3: First real workflow, hands-on (30 min)</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Pick the most relevant Project for their role.</li><li>Walk through one full real-work use, step by step.</li><li>Have each person do their own example with a real input from their own work.</li><li>Office hour scheduled for 1 week later.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Week 2-4</span><h2 class="h2">Reinforcement &amp; refinement</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Weekly office hours with the AI lead. Anyone can come; bring real work that is not flowing.</li><li>Slack channel for prompt sharing. "This prompt worked great" or "Why is Claude refusing X?"</li><li>Workflow owners check in 1:1 with each team member to see what's actually being used.</li><li>Update the Project knowledge based on patterns from real use.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Role-specific exercises</span><h2 class="h2">What to have each function do</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>First workflow</th><th>Time to fluency</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Sales rep</td><td>Draft a follow-up email from real call notes</td><td>1-2 sessions</td></tr><tr><td>Marketer</td><td>Draft a content brief from a topic + target keyword</td><td>2-3 sessions</td></tr><tr><td>CSM</td><td>Build a QBR pack from usage data + account notes</td><td>2-3 sessions</td></tr><tr><td>Executive</td><td>Get a one-page brief from a board doc</td><td>1-2 sessions</td></tr><tr><td>Ops</td><td>Summarize meeting notes into action items + decisions</td><td>1 session</td></tr><tr><td>Support</td><td>Draft a reply to a real ticket</td><td>1-2 sessions</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Common failure modes</span><h2 class="h2">Where adoption stalls</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>People use Claude once, get a meh output, give up.</strong> Fix: show them how to iterate. "More concise, shorter, add X" turns a meh draft into a good one in 30 seconds.</li><li><strong>People use it for the wrong workflows.</strong> Fix: be explicit about the workflows where it shines vs the workflows where it does not yet.</li><li><strong>People do not have time.</strong> Fix: assign protected calendar time for the first two weeks. "Use Claude for 30 min/day, every day, for the next 10 work days."</li><li><strong>People do not trust the output.</strong> Fix: review some of their outputs together. Build trust calibration. Show what Claude is reliably good at and what needs human verification.</li><li><strong>The Project is not loaded with the right knowledge.</strong> Fix: iterate. Most Projects need 3-4 rounds of knowledge updates before they hum.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Measuring adoption</span><h2 class="h2">How to know it's working</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Usage frequency:</strong> are people using Claude weekly, daily, or never? Daily users adopt; weekly users sometimes; never-users will never absent intervention.</li><li><strong>Workflow output:</strong> are proposals/content/replies actually shipping faster, with the AI tool?</li><li><strong>Voluntary sharing:</strong> are people posting prompts and patterns in the Slack channel without being asked? That's the strongest signal of organic adoption.</li><li><strong>1:1 check-ins:</strong> ask each person, "what's the workflow you use Claude for most often?" If they can name one, they're adopted. If they can't, they're not.</li></ul></div></section>

